    "objectID": "intro.html",
    "href": "intro.html",
    "title": "How we do this",
    "section": "",
    "text": "Backgammon decisions split more or less naturally into “positional” and “technical” problems.\nThe positional decisions require vision: Game plan, structural patterns, importance of points – all the more qualitative stuff.\nTechnical decisions, on the other hand, require counting: Shots, rolls and pips – the quantitative stuff.\nBoth types of positions, positional and technical, of course have both checker plays and cube plays (double and take decisions). So all in all we have four broad categories. Within those we focus on concepts for checker plays (splitting, hitting loose, etc).\nFor cube decisions we try find typical positions for: a) a minimal double, b) a solid double and solid take, c) a minimal take.\nLet’s go.",
    "crumbs": [
      "How we do this"
    ]
